{"id":"2109.11764","submitter":"Somabha Mukherjee","authors":"Somabha Mukherjee, Jaesung Son, Swarnadip Ghosh, Sourav Mukherjee","title":"Efficient Estimation in Tensor Ising Models","comments":"38 pages, 10 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST math-ph math.MP math.PR stat.TH","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  The tensor Ising model is a discrete exponential family used for modeling\nbinary data on networks with not just pairwise, but higher-order dependencies.\nA particularly important class of tensor Ising models are the tensor\nCurie-Weiss models, where all tuples of nodes of a particular order interact\nwith the same intensity. The maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) is not explicit\nin this model, due to the presence of an intractable normalizing constant in\nthe likelihood, and a computationally efficient alternative is to use the\nmaximum pseudolikelihood estimator (MPLE). In this paper, we show that the MPLE\nis in fact as efficient as the MLE (in the Bahadur sense) in the $2$-spin\nmodel, and for all values of the null parameter above $\\log 2$ in higher-order\ntensor models. Even if the null parameter happens to lie within the very small\nwindow between the threshold and $\\log 2$, they are equally efficient unless\nthe alternative parameter is large. Therefore, not only is the MPLE\ncomputationally preferable to the MLE, but also theoretically as efficient as\nthe MLE over most of the parameter space. Our results extend to the more\ngeneral class of Erd\\H{o}s-R\\'enyi hypergraph Ising models, under slight\nsparsities too.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 24 Sep 2021 06:28:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 10 Dec 2021 14:15:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 4 Mar 2022 05:43:59 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 20 Dec 2022 08:47:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-21"}
